article.description: Jason Kidd scored 30 points on an uncharacteristic 25 shots as the New Jersey Nets pulled away for a 93-82 victory over the Washington Wizards, who watched Michael Jordan take no shots in the fourth quarter.
article.headline: Nets beat an MJ team for first time since '85

images.name: Kidd, Jason 020221 inline
images.caption: Jason Kidd got the best of the Wizards with 30 points, eight assists and seven rebounds.

article.linkText: Kidd pilots Nets to easy win over 'disconnected' Wiz
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- If Jason Kidd keeps making 40-foot bank shots at the buzzer, his shooting percentage might just be as respectable as his team's record. Kidd nailed one at the end of the third quarter Thursday night, the key moment in a 17-2 rally that gave the New Jersey Nets a 93-82 victory over the slumping Washington Wizards. "That's why my percentage is so low -- because I take those shots," said Kidd, often mentioned as an MVP candidate while catching flak for his 38 percent shooting. "But I like taking those shots because if you don't take them, you don't know if they might go." Kidd had 30 points, eight assists and seven rebounds as the Nets got their first road victory over Michael Jordan since a 117-113 victory over the Chicago Bulls on March 3, 1985. They had lost 23 straight on Jordan's home courts -- 22 at Chicago and one at the MCI Center this season. Kerry Kittles added 20 points for the Nets, who won their fourth straight by literally running past the lethargic Wizards. New Jersey had a 27-0 advantage in fast-break points, nearly matching a 31-0 advantage in a 111-67 home victory over Washington on Jan. 16. "Most teams are slow at getting back," Kittles said. "But we're running it right back down your throats as soon as you score." Jordan, who missed Wednesday night's game at Detroit because of a sore knee, had 16 points on 7-for-17 shooting, six assists and five rebounds in 37 minutes. Richard Hamilton scored 15 points but shot just 5-of-13, while Popeye Jones had 10 points and 12 rebounds as the Wizards lost for the fifth time in six games since the All-Star break. "We're right now emotionally and physically on empty," Washington coach Doug Collins said. "And that was my biggest concern coming back from the All-Star break with this schedule. We've got to somehow find some energy. We're a very tired team." Collins said he was giving his team a day off Friday "to think about the commitment we made the first 50 games this season to get the approval of this crowd and be respected in the NBA." "We've worked too hard to allow that to slip away," Collins said. Even Jordan lacked his usual energy, a result of his layoff with the ailing knee and the frantic wheeling and dealing that always precedes the NBA trading deadline. Though he no longer technically holds a front office position, Jordan still runs the team. "Today, I don't think any of us was in sync," Jordan said. "I certainly didn't have rhythm. ... We have to reach deep inside ourselves and stay connected. Today, I think we were disconnected." Kidd scored 12 points, including 10 in a row, in the 17-2 run that put the Nets ahead 81-65 early in the fourth quarter. The unlikely pair of Hubert Davis and Christian Laettner cut the Wizards' deficit to seven with 5:34 to play, but two free throws by Richard Jefferson and a layup by Kidd put the lead back in double digits. Kidd converted back-to-back layups after a pair of steals -- one by him and one by Jefferson -- in an 11-5 run that gave the Nets a 46-39 lead at halftime. The Wizards' only field goal over the final 4:51 of the half came on a goaltending call on a layup by Hamilton. The Wizards worked hard to cut the lead to one late in the third quarter, but Kidd's 40-footer put the Nets up by six and swung the momentum. "Jason Kidd banks that one in; it's a downer," Collins said. "It's a deflating kind of play."

Game notes
Nets starting center Todd MacCulloch, trying to play on the injured foot that caused him to miss Tuesday's game against Golden State, lasted just seven minutes before leaving for good in the first quarter. ... Neither team made a move on trade deadline day. Collins said Jordan "was in the office all day working the phones," but the team never came close to making a deal. "I can't see where there was deal on the table that suited this organization," Jordan said. "Let's now make a dumb deal." ... Jordan got kneed in the thigh on a tip-in by Jahidi White in the third quarter, but it only caused him to leave the game for less than a minute. ... Although Kidd had a great game, his streak of six straight double-doubles came to an end.
